  "response_text": "As a mother of a 2-year-old, it's essential to prioritize whole, nutrient-dense foods to support your child's growth and development, as well as your own overall health. Here's a healthy grocery list to get you started:\n\n**Fresh Fruits:**\n\n1. Apples\n2. Bananas\n3. Avocados\n4. Berries (strawberries, blueberries, raspberries)\n5. Oranges\n6. Grapes (cut in half to reduce choking risk)\n7. Mangoes\n8. Pineapples\n9. Watermelon\n10. Peaches\n\n**Fresh Vegetables:**\n\n1. Carrots\n2. Broccoli\n3. Sweet potatoes\n4. Spinach\n5. Bell peppers\n6. Cucumbers\n7. Cherry tomatoes\n8. Zucchini\n9. Corn\n10. Green beans\n\n**Proteins:**\n\n1. Boneless, skinless chicken breasts\n2. Ground turkey\n3. Salmon fillets\n4. Tuna canned in water\n5. Eggs\n6. Greek yogurt\n7. Cottage cheese\n8. Almonds\n9. Chia seeds\n10. Quinoa\n\n**Whole Grains:**\n\n1. Brown rice\n2. Quinoa\n3. Whole wheat bread\n4. Whole grain pasta\n5. Oats\n6. Whole grain cereals\n7. Whole wheat crackers\n\n**Dairy:**\n\n1. Low-fat milk\n2. Greek yogurt\n3. Cottage cheese\n4. Shredded cheese (part-skim mozzarella, reduced-fat cheddar)\n\n**Healthy Fats:**\n\n1. Avocado oil\n2. Olive oil\n3. Coconut oil\n4. Nuts and seeds (almonds, walnuts, chia seeds)\n\n**Snacks:**\n\n1. Fresh fruit\n2. Cut veggies with hummus\n3. Whole grain crackers with cheese or peanut butter\n4. Yogurt\n5. Homemade trail mix with nuts and dried fruits\n\n**Beverages:**\n\n1. Water\n2. Low-fat milk\n3. 100% fruit juice (diluted with water for toddlers)\n4. Herbal tea (for mom)\n\n**Pantry Staples:**\n\n1. Canned black beans, chickpeas, and tomatoes\n2. Lentils\n3. Whole grain pasta sauce\n4. Oats\n5. Granola\n6. Nuts and seeds\n7. Dried fruits\n8. Honey or maple syrup (for mom)\n\n**Tips:**\n\n1. Choose organic options when possible, especially for fruits and veggies with high pesticide residue.\n2. Buy in bulk and plan meals around seasonal produce to save money.\n3. Involve your child in the grocery shopping process to teach them about different foods and encourage healthy eating habits.\n4. Consider a \"toddler-friendly\" shopping list with pictures or simple labels to help your child identify their favorite foods.\n\nRemember, this list is just a starting point, and you can adjust it based on your family's preferences and dietary needs. Happy shopping and healthy eating!",
